**Solution 1:** Simply use built-in methods, from [Stefan Pochmann](https://leetcode.com/StefanPochmann/)
```python
class Solution:
    def detectCapitalUse(self, w: str) -> bool:
        return w.isupper() or w.islower() or w.istitle()
```
```isupper()```: Check if all the characters in the text are in upper case
```islower()```: Check if all the characters in the text are in lower case
```istitle()```: Check if each word start with an upper case letter

**Solution 2:** Don't use ```istitle()```, from [Gene](https://leetcode.com/GeneGo/)
Note that, if len(w)==1, it is True because the third case "Only the first letter in this word is capital, like "Google"." can only apply to w if len(w)>1
```python
class Solution:
    def detectCapitalUse(self, w: str) -> bool:
        return len(w)==1 or w[1:].islower() or w.isupper()
```

**Solution 3:** Convert ```w``` to the correct format and check if it changed, from [Lam Nguyen](https://leetcode.com/nguyenla/)
```python
class Solution:
    def detectCapitalUse(self, w: str) -> bool:
        return w[1:].lower() == w[1:] or w.lower() == w or w.upper() == w
```

**Solution 4:** Same idea but use ```capitalize()```, from [llx](https://leetcode.com/llx9/)
```python
class Solution:
    def detectCapitalUse(self, w: str) -> bool:
        return w in [w.upper(), w.lower(), w.capitalize()]
```

Please leave any other fun solutions in the comments.
**Happy New Year!**

The above ones are really nice for contests, and the below ones should be better in an interview.

**Solution 5:** Count upper/lower case letters
 - Count the number of uppercase (```up```) and lowercase (```low```) letters in the word.
 - If the number of uppercase letters is the same as the length of the word, return True. (This means All letters in this word are capitals.)
 - If the number of the lowercase is the same as the length of the word, return True. (This means All letters in this word are not capitals.)
 - If the number of uppercase is 1, and the first letter is uppercase, return True. (This means Only the first letter in this word is capital.)

```python
class Solution:
    def detectCapitalUse(self, w: str) -> bool:
        up = low = 0
        for c in w:
            if c.isupper():
                up += 1
            else:
                low += 1
        return up==len(w) or low==len(w) or (up==1 and w[0].isupper())
```

**Solution 6:** No APIs
```python
class Solution:
    def detectCapitalUse(self, w: str) -> bool:
        up = low = 0
        uppercase = set('ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ')
        # uppercase = set(ascii_uppercase)
        for c in w:
            if c in uppercase:
                up += 1
            else:
            	low += 1
        return up==len(w) or low==len(w) or (up==1 and w[0] in uppercase)
```

**Solution 7:** Do a little bit blance:
```python
class Solution:
    def detectCapitalUse(self, w: str) -> bool:
        upLow = 0
        for c in w:
            upLow += 1 if c.islower() else -1
        return abs(upLow)==len(w) or (upLow==len(w)-2 and w[0].isupper())
```

