Dont reinvent the wheel, just use the STL:
- [std::all_of](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/algorithm/all_any_none_of)
- [std::isupper](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/string/byte/isupper)
- [std::islower](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/string/byte/islower)

Will be even simpler with C++20 :-)
```	
bool detectCapitalUse(string word) {
	return all_of(word.begin(), word.end(), ::islower)
		or all_of(word.begin(), word.end(), ::isupper)
		or (isupper(word.front()) and all_of(next(word.begin()), word.end(), ::islower));
}
```
****
**Wait a minute! The title says 2 Lines, I see 3!**

As a  smart friend made me remark, both "Leetcode" and "leetcode" are valid, so the capitalisation of the first letter does not matter. IE "all letters lower case OR (first letter upper case AND all letters minus first letter lower case)" is equivalent to:
 "all letters minus first letter lower case". 
```
bool detectCapitalUse(string word) {
	return all_of(word.begin(), word.end(), ::isupper)
		or all_of(next(word.begin()), word.end(), ::islower);
}
```
****
**Why `::islower` and not just `islower` or  `std::islower`  here?**
`islower` is defined in multiple headers and also is the C library, I dont control what header leetcode is including.
by using `::islower` we actually call the C function defined in global namespace.
****
**Daim! I want to use the C++ std::islower function and not the C ::islower function!**

1 - Using a lambda: 

```
all_of(word.begin(), word.end(), [](char c){return std::isupper(c);})
```
That's valid but it is a bit defeating the purpose of the expressiveness / simplicity of the code.

2 - Forcing the compiler to use the C++ function we want (`std::islower):

As mentioned in the previous paragraph there are multiple definitions of islower :
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/6b359918-fab1-4b4f-b68a-be120c023dc5_1596306428.634877.png)
[link on cppreference](https://en.cppreference.com/mwiki/index.php?title=Special%3ASearch&search=islower)

I had this disussion with my friend and we were a bit annoyed to use the old C function instead of relying purely on the C++ library. Unfortunately, the compiler does not see the `std::islower` defined in `<cctype>` he sees the one that is overloaded in `<clocale>` that takes an extra *locale* argument (and then the code does not compile).

How to force the compiler to force using an overload? Using a cast is a way (there is maybe a better way to do that).

in `<cctype>`, `islower` is defined like this: `int islower( int ch );`
so we can do: 
```
all_of(word.begin(), word.end(), static_cast<int(*)(int)>(islower))
```
Hum that's a bit ugly and cryptic.

We can still define an alias for that type: `using cctype = int(*)(int);`
Therefore the code becomes:
```
using cctype = int(*)(int); // function pointer type used to force use 
			                // the overload defined in cctype header
bool detectCapitalUse(const string& word) const {
    return all_of(word.cbegin(), word.cend(), cctype(isupper))
			or all_of(next(word.cbegin()), word.cend(), cctype(islower));
}
```
**EDIT: What if the interviewer is not happy with this?**

Well, you can argue that this is the code he would like to see in production, but maybe the interviwer wants to see you can program the whole logic,
therefore you can write your own `is_upper`, `is_lower` and `all_of` :

```
namespace mystd{

	// see https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2169261/c-isupper-function
	// for more serious implementation

	bool is_lower(char c){
		return (c >= 'a' && c <= 'z');
	}

	bool is_upper(char c){
		return (c >= 'A' && c <= 'Z');
	}

	// copy pasted from cpp reference
	// note that the interviewer might be a bit pissed there :-)
	template<class InputIt, class UnaryPredicate >
	constexpr bool all_of(InputIt first, InputIt last, UnaryPredicate p){
		return std::find_if_not(first, last, p) == last;  // lol :-)
	}

	// alternate version to not piss an irritable interviewer
	template<typename IT, typename Pred>
	bool all_of(IT begin, IT end, Pred p){
		for(auto it = begin; it != end; ++it){
			if(!p(*it))
				return false;
		}
		return true;
	}
}
```

Please comment if you have a better approach / suggestion to that specific problem.

