This question was a good opportunity for me to pactice implementation of DFA for regular expression in C++. 
I implimented Moore State machine with 5 states using switch statement in C++.
Even though this regex can be easy checked in JAVA. 
Please find below the image with the state diagram. Only Q4 will generate false input because it violates regex.

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/2b16d76b-465a-4cb5-8ee9-544d202435be_1643047210.962247.jpeg)

C++ Implementation :
```
class Solution {
    int curstate;
    bool input(char c) {
        switch(curstate) {
                // a : (c >= 'A' && c <= 'Z')
                // b : (c >= 'a' && c <= 'z')
            case 0:
                curstate = (c >= 'a' && c <= 'z') ? 3 : 1;
                break;
            case 1:
                curstate = (c >= 'a' && c <= 'z') ? 3 : 2;
                break;
            case 2:
                curstate = (c >= 'a' && c <= 'z') ? 4 : 2;
                break;
            case 3:
                curstate = (c >= 'a' && c <= 'z') ? 3 : 4;
                break;
            case 4:
            default:
                return false;
        }
        return curstate != 4;
    }
public:
    Solution() : curstate(0) {}
    bool detectCapitalUse(string word) {
        int i = 0;
        while(i < word.size() && input(word[i])) i++;
        return curstate != 4;
    }
};
```


